Sentencing proceeds.   State advises the Court they have complied with victim notification.  Statements by the State, defense counsel and defendant.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
- 90 Days of condition time in the House of Correction.  Condition time to be STAYED for use by the probation agent.  For the first violation, 10 days to be served; for the second violation 20 days to be served; for the third violation 60 days to be served.
- AODA assessment and comply with any recommended treatment
- Absolute Sobriety
- No drugs without a valid prescription
- Random screens and testing be monthly at a minimum
- Seek and maintain full-time employment
- No association with drug users or drug dealers and no contact where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged or distributed.
- Make child support payments
- No fine
- Pay all costs, fees, assessments and surcharges during the term of probation or serve 10 days in the House of Correction, consecutive.  Any amounts remaining is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.
- Pay all supervision fees.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.

- defendant to provide a DNA sample and pay the surcharge, if not already done.

Defendant Jason L Latimore in court with attorney Victoria M McCandless.  Dennis P Murphy appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of State, Court ordered PENALTY ENHANCER is dismissed.

Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgment of conviction entered.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court also advises defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Court adjourns sentencing for defendant to bring in work schedule.
